I've done some interesting world-building for species before. A rule of thumb I worked with was that humans usually have one child, but two boobs. Twins and triplets are much more rare. In older times, triplets were highly unusual, and often one would die, back in the bad old days of extremely high infant mortality.

Loosely based on that, and cats & dogs (domestic and wild cousins), I considered that anthros would have more children per pregnancy than humans, but that large litters of four or more would be at least as rare as triplets just due to food and energy requirements. So I settled on 8 nipples as vestigial heritage for general felid & canid anthros, and that twins was pretty much the standard expected pregnancy. Triplets would be almost as common, but quadruplets and more would be rare and more likely when the mother is very well fred and healthy.

For anthros of different species, I make adjustments. Mares have a pair of boobs and usually have a single foal, while pigs and rodents might have ten teats and litters of 5 or 6 as normal. I've never tried to force strict animal anatomy on an anthro, but use feral anatomy as a guideline to imagine differences from humans. All my anthros have hands, for example. But, some have four or six total digits. And, my cats have retractable claws, not sharp fingernails.

Also why my anthros have A- and B-cup tiddies, or smaller. They usually only approach C-cup when pregnant & nursing, and even then their lower belly teats are A-cup at most.

pic-related: If I was drawing that, I'd have made her top set of boobs about the same size as her second set below that. Barely just perceptibly larger, maybe.
